1.One paragraph on the motivation for the analysis.

The motivation of this cost & benefit analysis is to predict whether or not the householders will take the credit and repair their houses. If we could use machine learning method to build logistics model and precisely predict the True Positive(the people who will take the credit and the model predict them),and minimize the number of False Negative (the people who will take the credit, but the model dose not predict them), we could minimize the loss of untargeted marketing and maxmize the total benefits of both the householders and the government.

2.Develop and interpret data visualizations that describe feature importance.

Below I create facetted plots of the percentage of saying yes for each variables. First, use gather to calculate each variables percentage of yes and no. Second, filter out yes for each variable and plot them. Third, I compare the facetted plots and find out the variables which have some specific categories that the percentage of these categories of saying yes tend to be much higher than the others. The light bule bars in the plots indicate that these categories tend to have percentage over 17% of say yes, which is higher than the number of people saying yes/ the whole number of people (10.9%).

This may provide instructions for my feature engineerings below.

cg <- cr %>%
  dplyr::select(-y_numeric,-X,-inflation_rate,-taxLien) %>% 
  gather(Variable, value, -y) %>%
  count(Variable,value,y)

cgyes <- subset(cg,cg$y=="yes")
cgno <- subset(cg,cg$y=="no")
names(cgyes)[4] <- "yes"
names(cgno)[4] <- "no"
cg_new <- merge(cgno,cgyes,by=c("Variable","value"),all=T)

cg_new[is.na(cg_new)] <- 0

cg_new$percent <- cg_new$yes/(cg_new$no+cg_new$yes)
cg_new$useful <- ifelse(cg_new$percent>0.15,1,0)

cg_new %>% 
  ggplot(., aes(value, percent,fill=useful)) +   
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  facet_wrap(~Variable, scales="free",ncol=3) +
  labs(x="Take credit or not", y="Value",
       title = "Category Feature associations with the likelihood of taking credit") +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

4.Engineer new features

a.Interpret your new features in one paragraph.

As can be seen from the explanary analysis in Chapter 2, there are many variables where in some of their categories, for example, people older than 60, the proportion of saying yes (thats to say, take the credit) is obviously higher than the other categoroies. Therefore, I use the following steps to do the featuring engineering.

  • First, I add interaction terms into new category to make more specific categories and improve the precision of the training moedel. For example, I noticed that occupation, education, marital status are all important variables in the model. I add a variable of occpation + education + marital status to make more detailed classifications hence providing more precised predicting model.

  • Second, I turn the continuous variables into dummy variables(categories). For instance, I find that people older than 60 and younger than 22 have a much higher percentage to say yes. Then I create a variable called age_cat to mark the people who are older than 60 or younger than 22, to train my model.

  • Third, I delete those variables which have minor or no impact on the model.

c.Plot the confusion metric outcomes for each Threshold.

It can be concluded from the plots below that we should find a threshold to maximam our total benefits.

iterateThresholds <- function(data) {
  x = .01
  all_prediction <- data.frame()
  while (x <= 1) {
  
  this_prediction <-
      testProbs %>%
      mutate(predOutcome = ifelse(Probs > x, 1, 0)) %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
     gather(Variable, Count) %>%
     mutate(Revenue =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative", Count * 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive",(66000-2850-5000)*(Count * 0.8)-2850*(Count * 0.2),
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", 0 * Count,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", (-2850) * Count,0)))),
            Threshold = x)
  
  all_prediction <- rbind(all_prediction, this_prediction)
  x <- x + .01
  }
return(all_prediction)
}
whichThreshold <- iterateThresholds(testProbs)

7.Conclusions

  • Conclude whether and why this model should or shouldnt be put into production. What could make the model better? What would you do to ensure that the marekting materials resulted in a better response rate?

Personally speaking, I think this model could be put into production because it has taken many feature engineering and has a relatively high percent of sensitivity, which means we could predict most of the people who will take the credit correctly. To make this model better, we could engineered more targeted features to improve the wide distribution of the sensitivity in the cross validation. To ensure a better response rate, we could only send marketing materials to those true positive we predict.
